<subSubSection lastPageId="55" lastPageNumber="56" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1437,1691,2042]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1907,1933]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Remarks.</emphasis>
This easily recognized species is the only species of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1842" box="[951,1068,1907,1933]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Syritta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latitarsata">
<emphasis box="[951,1068,1907,1933]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">latitarsata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group occurring in large areas of the Afrotropical region but apparently not in the central area and East Africa (
<bibRefCitation author="Lyneborg, L. &amp; Barkemeyer, W." pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="1 - 224" refId="ref37423" refString="Lyneborg, L. &amp; Barkemeyer, W. (2005) A world revision of the genus Syritta Le Peletier &amp; Serville, 1828 (Diptera: Syrphidae). Entomonograph, 15, 1 - 224." type="journal article" year="2005">Lyneborg &amp; Barkemeyer 2005</bibRefCitation>
). It can be differentiated from all its congeners by all the tarsomeres of the hind legs being broadened and flattened (
<bibRefCitation author="Lyneborg, L. &amp; Barkemeyer, W." box="[226,576,2015,2042]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="1 - 224" refId="ref37423" refString="Lyneborg, L. &amp; Barkemeyer, W. (2005) A world revision of the genus Syritta Le Peletier &amp; Serville, 1828 (Diptera: Syrphidae). Entomonograph, 15, 1 - 224." type="journal article" year="2005">Lyneborg &amp; Barkemeyer 2005</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
